1 [a] Estimate the accuracy of your classifier. Is your value reasonable?

A streaming classifier was then created to identify eye movements in real time. The mechanics of this classifier are as follows:

  • Window Size: file sampling rate
  • Increment: one third of the Window Size
  • Event Detection: completed using zero crossings under a threshold value of 70

In essence, a window of values was isolated. The number of zero crossings was calculated for this window, and if it was less than a threshold value, the algorithm identified that an event occurred in this window. Classification was then completed as detailed below. From here, the window was moved across by the increment and so on until the end of the .wav file. The combination of individual classifications were combined to become the final string prediction.

Event Classification

One significant issue with the above method was that multiple windows would give a prediction for the same event given that the increment was less than the window. Since an arbitrary window could contain only part of an event, errors were made. Increasing the increment size was unfeasible since it reduced the granularity of the classifier and introduced missed events.

As a result, we define an event subsequence as consecutive event predictions, enclosed on both sides by a lack of events. Where NE represents No Event, given the following progression: NE, NE, L, L, R, NE, the event subsequence would be LLR. For each event subsequence, the final prediction for a single eye movement is defined as the majority class (L, in the example).

In doing so, it was important that the increments were small, and the threshold was relatively large. The intuition was that by having multiple predictions for the same eye movement event, classification errors from a window only partially containing the event would be mitigated against.

# simple decision rule
LR_detection = function(seq) {
  maxval = which.max(seq)
  minval = which.min(seq)
  movement = ifelse(maxval < minval,  "L", "R")
  return(movement)
}

streaming_classifier = function(wave_file,  
                                window_size = wave_file@samp.rate,
                                increment = window_size/10) {
  Y = wave_file@left
  xtime = seq_len(length(wave_file@left))/wave_file@samp.rate 
  predicted_labels = c()
  lower_interval = 1
  max_time = max(xtime)*window_size
  
  sequence <- FALSE
  # keeping count of the number of L and R in a given event subsequence, curr_sequence[1] being L, and [2] being R
  curr_sequence <- c(0, 0)
  while(max_time > lower_interval + window_size) {
    
    upper_interval = lower_interval + window_size
    interval = Y[lower_interval:upper_interval]
    
    # zero crossings to identify if an event existed within a window
    zero_crossings = sum(interval[1:(length(interval) - 1)] * interval[2:(length(interval))] <= 0)
    
    if (zero_crossings <= 70) {
      predicted = LR_detection(interval)
      if (predicted == "L") {
        curr_sequence <- c(curr_sequence[1] + 1, curr_sequence[2])
      } else {
        curr_sequence <- c(curr_sequence[1], curr_sequence[2]+1)
      }
      sequence <- TRUE
      
    } else {
      if (sequence == TRUE) {
        # determining majority class
        if (curr_sequence[1] >= curr_sequence[2]) {
          predicted_labels = c(predicted_labels, "L")
        } else {
          predicted_labels = c(predicted_labels, "R")
        } 
      }
      sequence <- FALSE
      curr_sequence <- c(0,0)
    }
    
    lower_interval = lower_interval + increment 
  } ## end while
  
  return(paste(predicted_labels, collapse=''))
}## end function

Having created the streaming classifier, predicted labels were found for all test .wav files, and stored in a list. A similarity score was then determined for each predicted label vs target label, and the overall accuracy was found by averaging the similarity scores of each .wav file.

The similarity score was based off the Levenshtein distance, which determined the minimum number of insertions, deletions and substitutions needed to transform one string into the other. For the purposes of this classifier, raw Levenshtein distance scores were difficult to interpret, especially since longer .wav files were likely to contain more errors. Alternative metrics included the Damerau–Levenshtein distance, although this was not chosen since it allowed transpositions. This was not appropriate since eye movements happened sequentially, and so two incorrect predictions for two separate events could not reasonably be swapped.

The similarity score is thus defined as:

\[ \text{Similarity Measure} = 1-{\text{Levenshtein Distance(A, B)} \over \text{max}(|A|, |B|)} \\ \text{where A is the target string, and B is the predicted value} \]

In this case, the Levenshtein distance over the longer of the two strings detailed how incorrect the prediction was. Assuming that a score of 1 indicates a perfect prediction thus gives the formula above.

# applying the streaming classifier to each .wav file
all_predicted_labels <- c()
for (i in 1:length(all_wave_files)) {
  all_predicted_labels <- c(all_predicted_labels, streaming_classifier(all_wave_files[[i]]))
}

# calculating similarity measure
prediction_accuracies <- c()
for (i in 1:length(all_predicted_labels)) {
  lv_distance <- stringdist(all_predicted_labels[i], all_target_labels[i], method="lv")
  len_predicted <- length(as.vector(strsplit(all_predicted_labels[i], "")[[1]]))
  len_target <- length(as.vector(strsplit(all_target_labels[i], "")[[1]]))
  longest_string <- max(c(len_predicted, len_target))
  prediction_accuracies <- append(prediction_accuracies, 1-lv_distance/longest_string)
}

#calculating overall accuracy
overall_accuracy <- mean(prediction_accuracies)
print(paste("Overall Accuracy:", round(overall_accuracy,2)))
## [1] "Overall Accuracy: 0.91"

The number above is the accuracy of the streaming classifier in correctly predicting results. It can be concluded that the classifier was effective on a broad level. It is also a reasonable score. A visual comparison of target strings versus predicted strings shows that predictions contained only minor errors. Furthermore, given that eye movement events followed such a distinct pattern, these results are not infeasible.

2 [a] Build a classifier using support vector machine (SVM) to predict the outcome of graft survival and generate a prevalidated outcome from the gene expression data.

Given a matrix of gene expression data, the aim was to identify the genes that were differentially expressed between stable and rejection patients. This was done using by fitting a series of linear models using the limma package.

Oddly, when filtering for genes with an adjusted p-value of less than 0.05, the logistic model produced at the bottom of this section displayed some odd results i.e. SVM was insignificant. It is assumed that tiny variances may have driven the t-values. The gene expression data was thus filtered by absolute value log fold change - these are the genes which are significantly expressed more either within the Stable or Rejection group.

design <- model.matrix(~Outcome, data = pData(gse))
fit <- lmFit(eMat, design)
fit <- eBayes(fit)

# sorting genes by log FC
tT <- topTable(fit, n = Inf) %>% top_n(abs(logFC), n=50)

All 50 genes were taken to build a pre-validated outcome using support vector machine (SVM).

In this stage, the expression matrix features were reduced to the 50 identified. The patients were divided into five folds, with one fold left out. The remaining four folds were used to derive the support vector machine prediction rule. The prediction rule was used to predict the outcome of the test group, and this was repeated for all five folds.

These outcomes were collected into a vector such that a prediction existed for each patient, and the accuracy was calculated with the target outcome vector, which is seen below.

# isolating significant genes and subsetting expression matrix 
DE_eMat <- eMat[rownames(tT), ]

# tranposing matrix for use in SVM
X <- as.matrix(t(DE_eMat))
y = gse$Outcome

# creating 5 folds
cvK = 5  
cvSets = cvTools::cvFolds(length(y), cvK)

# pre-validated vector
pre_validated <- vector(, length(y))

for (j in 1:cvK) {
    test_id = cvSets$subsets[cvSets$which == j]
    
    X_test = X[test_id, ]
    X_train = X[-test_id, ]
    y_test = y[test_id]
    y_train = y[-test_id]
    svm_res = e1071::svm(x = X_train, y = as.factor(y_train))
    fit <- predict(svm_res, X_test)
    
    for (b in 1:length(test_id)) {
      pre_validated[test_id[b]] <- paste0(fit[[b]], "")
    }
}

count = 0
for (i in 1:length(pre_validated)) {
  if (pre_validated[i] == gse$Outcome[i]) {
    count = count + 1
  }
}

accuracy = count/length(pre_validated)
accuracy
## [1] 0.85

At this point, a logistic regression model was fitted. Using backwards AIC model selection gives the following model:

model.full = glm(Actual ~ ., data = patientData, family = binomial)
model.aic = step(model.full, direction = "backward", trace = FALSE)

\[ E(\hat{outcome}) = -2.833 + 4.679(\text{SVM Prediction}) \]

Despite this, it seemed more reasonable to provide a model with clinical variables included. As a result, a new logistic regression model was fitted with Age and Sex as well. Race was excluded as it had little bearing on the final result.

By analysing the coefficients below, it can be seen that the SVM prediction was the most significant factor by far with a p-value well below 0.05.

# 5 fold cross validation, calculating accuracy
K = 5  
cvSets = cvTools::cvFolds(nrow(patientData), K) 

X <- patientData
cv_acc <- vector(, length(y))

for (j in 1:K) {
    test_id = cvSets$subsets[cvSets$which == j]
    test = X[test_id, ]
    train = X[-test_id, ]
    glm.fit <- glm(Actual ~ Age + Sex + SVM_Prediction, data = train, family = binomial)
    predictions <- predict(glm.fit, test, type="response")
    
    for (b in 1:length(test_id)) {
      cv_acc[test_id[b]] <- ifelse(predictions[[b]] > 0.5, "Stable", "Rejection")
    }
}

count = 0
for (i in 1:length(cv_acc)) {
  if (cv_acc[i] == gse$Outcome[i]) {
    count = count + 1
  }
}

accuracy = count/length(cv_acc)

The final model was:

\[ E(\hat{outcome}) = -3.807 + 0.019(\text{Age}) -0.082(\text{Sex}_\text{Male}) + 4.663(\text{SVM Prediction}) \]

With 5 fold cross validation, the accuracy of this model was: 0.9.

3 [b] Build two classifier using randomForest to predict the outcome of graft survival using the genes selected in part (a).
3 [c] Preform repeated 5-fold cross validation for each of the data and calculate the accuracy. What is the average accuracy for blood vs biopsy biomarker model?

In this section, two randomForest classifiers were constructed. The first created used the biopsy data, where a 25 repeated 5 fold cross validation was completed. The accuracy of this model is seen below.

biopsy_eMat <- exprs(gse_biopsy)[rownames(biopsy_tT), ]

# tranposing matrix for use in SVM
X <- data.frame(t(biopsy_eMat))
X['Outcome'] <- factor(gse_biopsy$Outcome)

cvK = 5  # define the number of CV folds
cv_acc_biopsy_25times <- vector(, 25)

for (i in 1:25) {

  # permute all the data, into 5 folds
  cvSets = cvTools::cvFolds(nrow(X), cvK) 
  cv_acc_biopsy5 <- vector(, 5)

  for (j in 1:cvK) {
    test_id = cvSets$subsets[cvSets$which == j]
    X_test = X[test_id, ]
    X_train = X[-test_id, ]

    model_rf = randomForest(X_train[, -length(X_train)], X_train[, length(X_train)])
    fit_rf = predict(model_rf, newdata = X_test)
    comparisons <- vector(, length(fit_rf))

    for (b in 1:length(fit_rf)) {
      comparisons[b] <- as.numeric(fit_rf[b])
    }
    cv_acc_biopsy5[j] <- mean(comparisons == as.numeric(X_test[, length(X_test)]))
  }
  cv_acc_biopsy_25times[i] <- mean(cv_acc_biopsy5)
}

mean(cv_acc_biopsy_25times)
## [1] 0.7853091

The second created used blood gene expression data, where another 25 repeated 5 fold cross validation was completed. The accuracy of this model is again seen below.

      comparisons[b] <- as.numeric(fit_rf[b])
    }

4 [a] Use ggplot to visualize the percentage of bleaching in coral reefs on a world map and look at which areas of the world have the most severe coral bleaching.

In order to visualise the areas of the world with the most severe coral bleaching, some initial work is done on the dataset. THe first action taken was to filter for areas where average bleaching is over 25%, which is a significant amount of bleaching.

Secondly, given that a location may have multiple pieces of data regarding their bleaching levels and general statistics, only the most recent statistic was taken. This should mean that the following visualisation has the most up to date statistics.

From here, bleaching was plotted on a world map, with each dot representing an event. The size and colour of these dots represent the extent to which the area was bleached, and can be read from the legend to the side.

# filtering events for those where an average of 25% or more has bleached, then identifying the best 
reef_filtered <- reef %>% filter(Average_bleaching > 25)

# given two measurements for the same location, take the most recent
reef_filtered <- reef_filtered %>% group_by(Reef.ID) %>% slice(which.max(Year))

  geom_polygon(data = world_map, 
               aes(x=long, y=lat, group = group), 
               fill="black", alpha=0.3) + 
  
  # adding coral bleaching data points with size and colour reflecting severity
  geom_point(data = reef_filtered, 
             aes(x=ifelse(Longitude.Degrees < 0, Longitude.Degrees + 360, 
                          Longitude.Degrees),
                 y=Latitude.Degrees, 
                 size = Average_bleaching, 
                 color = Average_bleaching),
             alpha=0.2) + 
  
  scale_colour_viridis() +
  theme_minimal() +
  
  # adding labels
  labs(x = 'Longitude (Degrees)',
       y = 'Latitude (Degrees)', 
       size = 'Average Bleached (%)',
       color = 'Average Bleached (%)',
       title = "Percentage of Bleaching in Coral Reefs Globally (1998 - 2017)")

Visually, we can see the three sites/localities which have been most greatly impacted are:

  • The Gulf of Mexico
  • South East Asia, including Malaysia, Indonesia, Thailand
  • Madagascar
